A scene I'd love to see picked apart, in Spielberg's War of the Worlds,
there is a shot when they are escaping in a minivan right after the
first attack. It appears to be one continuous shot but it goes from
inside the van, out into the air, around and back into the van. It's a
pretty amazing shot really. A lot of good stuff in that movie (except
the damn aliens). Worth checking out, I think.

snippet.textDisplay: No! ZBrush was around back then but it was pretty much unknown and basically for high school kids to fart around with. If you really want to do something on the history of CGI go back to Lightwave not even Lightwave 3d. Just Lightwave. Shit was harder back in the day. Before Autodesk bought up everything. Talk about the fun shit like Vue D'Esprit and various Metacreations apps. You're in the industry but do you know its roots? There used to be a time when all this shit was rendered on SGI machines. snippet.textDisplay:
One point you guys have not really mentioned in these videos is how a lot of the editing errors you point are explained away by the writers with their cinematic universe and environments that can make some of these effects more forgivable. Here are some examples I thought of while watching your videos....


~Matrix looks plasticy with unfinished physics at points because it is in a simulation.
~Anakin rides the flea bag so oddly and his weight is not evenly distributing because he is pushing with the force to keep balance maybe.
~The weird flea bag isnt dragging its ass because of the distribution of mass, dense bomes up front and a sac of lighter fat at the back, hell it could be filled with helium for all we know about aliens.
~Marvel weapons are strong sure, but marvel enemies are also tougher, with some notable human exceptions, but its also like the spiderman rule of them always holding back so they can arrest the common baddies instead of killing them.


These are just signs of good fantasy and writing though that allows viewers to forgive some of this themselves as they watch because the universe is so well developed and portrayed that the audience will make their own rationalizations.

snippet.textDisplay:
It would be cool if you guys took some time to talk about your fellow animators on Youtube in Roosterteeth. There may be some good stuff to talk about with RWBY and Gen:Lock, but the real cool thing would be Red Vs. Blue, their transition from machinimation to traditional animation and how they blended the two in this ground breaking episode was amazing and would be a cool twist to one of your videos. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ke9wtbzGjCI
The way they built there own genre and animation studio from nothing is insanely impressive on its own, but they also improved at a breakneck pace you can see improving from episode to episode. This ones also cool too. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2dp2REMpi6k
snippet.textOriginal:
It would be cool if you guys took some time to talk about your fellow animators on Youtube in Roosterteeth. There may be some good stuff to talk about with RWBY and Gen:Lock, but the real cool thing would be Red Vs. Blue, their transition from machinimation to traditional animation and how they blended the two in this ground breaking episode was amazing and would be a cool twist to one of your videos. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Ke9wtbzGjCI
The way they built there own genre and animation studio from nothing is insanely impressive on its own, but they also improved at a breakneck pace you can see improving from episode to episode. This ones also cool too. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2dp2REMpi6k
